password, then updating the StatefulSet with the right image version, environment variables, volume mounts, and configuration. But I need to make sure I'm handling the initial master node bootstrap correctly for Elasticsearch 8.x.\n\nThe tricky part is that 8.x has security and auto-enrollment enabled by default, which can complicate things. I should disable auto-enrollment and configure everything manually by setting the security flags and password environment variable along with the TLS setup. When I delete and recreate the StatefulSet, the PVCs will stick around, but there's a compatibility issue between 7.x and 8.x data that I need to account for—the existing data won't be compatible with the new version.\n\nMy plan is to delete both the old StatefulSet and PVCs to start fresh, then generate TLS certificates that cover the service DNS names like `es-http.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`, `localhost`, and the IP address, create the necessary secrets and ConfigMap, deploy the new 8.11.1 StatefulSet, and finally verify everything works with HTTPS requests.\n\nFor the certificate verification mode, I'll use `certificate` instead of `full` to avoid hostname validation issues since all nodes share the same cert. The SANs need to include both the HTTP service names and the individual pod DNS names for the StatefulSet like `es-cluster-0.es-cluster`, `es-cluster-1.es-cluster`, and `es-cluster-2.es-cluster`.\n\nI also need to account for the version upgrade from 7.17.9 to 8.11.1 — the existing StatefulSet and its data will need to be migrated carefully, so I'll need to delete the old deployment first while preserving the PVCs.\n\nGenerating TLS certificates... Writing shell commands... Configuring SSL/TLS certificates for both HTTP and transport layer security...\n\nNow I'm setting up the StatefulSet with three Elasticsearch replicas, including an init container to fix file permissions and the main container running Elasticsearch 8.11.1 with exposed ports for client and n