ty and basic read/write operations. I should also verify there's no PodDisruptionBudget blocking the deletion process.\n\nThe existing services look good—the headless `es-cluster` service handles inter-node discovery on port 9300, while `es-http` provides client access on 9200. For testing connectivity, I'll need to handle the CA certificate so the curl-test pod can properly verify the HTTPS connection to Elasticsearch.\n\nOn the password front, I need something that meets ES 8.x requirements—at least 6 characters—so I'll go with \"elasticpassword123\" to ensure it passes any security validation.\n\nFor the cluster bootstrap, ES 8.x requires `cluster.initial_master_nodes` to be set. In a StatefulSet, the pods start sequentially, so es-cluster-0 will initialize first and wait for the other nodes to join via `discovery.seed_hosts`. Once es-cluster-1 and es-cluster-2 come up, they'll discover each other and the cluster will bootstrap successfully.\n\nNow I'm ready to write out all the commands to execute. Using an exec probe with curl would be better since it can reference the ELASTIC_PASSWORD environment variable directly, avoiding hardcoded credentials in the manifest. I should verify that curl is available in the Elasticsearch 8.11.1 Docker image, though it typically is included. All ES 8.x endpoints require authentication when security is enabled, so I need to go with the exec curl approach using the ELASTIC_PASSWORD environment variable for the readiness probe. This is more reliable than just checking if the port is open, and curl should be available in the ES Docker image.\n\nFor the httpGet probe with HTTPS, I can add a custom Authorization header with basic auth. Let me encode the credentials in base64 so I can include them in the probe configuration.\n\nI should use `/_cluster/health` without the wait parameter to avoid the probe hanging. I'll also set `initialDelaySeconds` to 30 since Elasticsearch with security takes longer to start up.\n\nWhen I recreate th