{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013FGdWXzeeMaE5xRS56LZjp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"ES is running and accepting HTTP connections (port 9200 is open with TLS), but it can't discover the other nodes because:\n1. DNS for `es-cluster-1.es-cluster` and `es-cluster-2.es-cluster` is failing\n2. The cluster hasn't formed yet because only es-cluster-0 is running\n\nThe issue is:\n1. The headless service `es-cluster` exists but it uses short names like `es-cluster-1.es-cluster` which needs to be `es-cluster-1.es-cluster.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` for the full DNS name, or just `es-cluster-1.es-cluster` within the same namespace.\n2. Within the elasticsearch namespace, the short form `es-cluster-1.es-cluster` should actually resolve since the DNS search domains should include `elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`, so the issue might be something else—maybe the other pods aren't running yet or there's a network policy blocking communication.\n\nActually, I'm realizing this is a classic bootstrap problem with Elasticsearch on Kubernetes: the StatefulSet creates pods sequentially and waits for each to be Ready before starting the next one, but Elasticsearch can't become Ready until it discovers other master nodes and forms a cluster. So es-cluster-0 is stuck waiting for es-cluster-1 and es-cluster-2 to exist, but they won't be created until es-cluster-0 is Ready.\n\nThe fix is either to use a simpler readiness probe like a TCP check so the first pod becomes Ready and allows the others to start, or switch to parallel pod creation with `podManagementPolicy: Parallel`. Looking at the current pod status, only es-cluster-0 is running, which confirms the sequential creation is blocked. The TCP socket approach would mark pods as Ready before the cluster is actually healthy, which isn't ideal. Instead, I'll use `podManagementPolicy: Parallel` to let all three pods start simultaneously—this way DNS entries for all nodes exist right away and the cluster can form properly while keeping the health check accurate. Since I can't patch this setting on an existing StatefulSet, I need to delete and recreate it with the Parallel policy.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1244,"cache_read_input_tokens":50755,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1244},"output_tokens":16,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6e9d8b53-b8fb-4a28-b615-c28f7434796f","uuid":"8d6cbeed-42bf-49c4-bc01-5443f88e84e0","request_id":"req_011CccGmhDWpBbx1vZUNV1xo"}
